{Good addition! It's important to help others get food.}

One day, the king of Zeboria asked Sam to (estimate) how much food they would need for the upcoming winter. After careful thought, Sam suggested they store (half) of the kingdom's entire harvest.

In this context, (estimate) means to make an educated guess, and (half) means splitting something into two equal parts. Here, Sam is using his math skills to help the kingdom prepare for winter.

{I'm glad you liked it!}

So, Sam began to (add) up all the food they had gathered. With the help of his friends, they managed to store (half) of it in the royal granary.

In our story, (add) means to combine or bring together, and (half) is used to indicate that they stored an equal portion of the total food, which is exactly half.

{Great idea! Sharing resources with neighboring villages is a kind act.}

The king agreed and sent Sam to deliver the (sum) of the remaining food to the neighboring village. After a long journey, Sam finally reached the village and presented the (sum) of their food.

In this part of the story, (sum) refers to the total amount of food that Sam brought to the neighboring village after adding all the different types of food together.

{That's okay, we can finish the story quickly.}

When Sam returned home, he decided to (add) up all the good deeds he had done that day. The acts of kindness he had performed were (equal) to the happiness he felt.

In our story, (add) means to count or tally, and (equal) means identical in amount, size, or value. So, Sam's happiness is just as great as the number of good deeds he did.

{Good idea, cookies are a great way to end the day!}

So, Sam decided to bake cookies, the number of cookies baked was (equal) to the number of friends he had. But, he had to (subtract) one cookie because he ate it while it was still warm.

In our story, (equal) means the same amount, so the number of cookies Sam baked was the same as the number of his friends. (Subtract) means to take away, so when Sam ate a cookie, the total number of cookies decreased by one.
